        <body id="d4">

            <div1 type="letter" n="1" id="d5">
                <head>Letter from Adelaide E. Case to Charles N. Tenney, <date value="1861-12-19"
                        >December 19th, 1861</date></head>

                <opener>

                    <pb n="1" entity="DSSR_000000766_0321"/>

                    <dateline><date value="1861-12-19">
                            <add hand="h1" place="inline">Dec 19</add>
                        </date>
                        <!-- added in different hand -->
                        <lb/>After school </dateline>

                    <salute>
                        <name type="person">Dear Charlie</name>
                    </salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I have returned<lb/> from school but how should I answer<lb/> your kind letter:
                    If I should answer<lb/> it as I<orig reg="received">recieved</orig>it; it would
                    be<lb/> with bitter oh, <hi rend="underline">such bitter</hi> tears.<lb/> Should
                    I tell you <hi rend="underline">why</hi> I wept?<lb/> No, dear Charlie I <hi
                        rend="underline">cannot now</hi> perhaps<lb/> I <hi rend="underline"
                    >never</hi> can, but be assured my<lb/> reasons are resistless. Dear
                    Charlie<lb/> my spirit has <hi rend="underline">striven</hi> to watch<lb/> over
                    and guard thee, and hourly<lb/> &amp; fervant prayers has risen to the<lb/>
                    throne of Grace for your safety.<lb/> But that prayer was only as a<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">true</hi> and <hi rend="underline">loving</hi> <hi
                        rend="underline">sister</hi> would<lb/> pray for a <hi rend="underline"
                        >brother.</hi> I have striven<lb/> aquired any other feeling save a<lb/>
                    sisterly love and Dear Charlie<del hand="h1">I</del><lb/>
                    <pb n="2" entity="DSSR_000000766_0322"/> if I have caused any other<lb/> feeling
                    to rise in your heart save<lb/> the feeling of friendship I <hi rend="underline"
                        >entreat</hi><lb/> of you to forgive me for I did<lb/> it unintentionly. And
                    if you<lb/> cherish such feelings toward me<lb/> Dear Charlie for my sake
                    and<lb/> for the sake of your future happiness<lb/> quench them. Promise me
                    that<lb/> you will. Only rem<add place="inline" hand="h1">em</add>ber me as a
                    sister or a friend.<lb/></p>

                <p> One would perhaps conclude<lb/> that I was the affiancied of an-<lb/> other, but
                    dear Charlie, <hi rend="underline">thank God<lb/> I am not</hi>--this may seem
                    strange<lb/> to you and if you demand my<lb/> reasons lay the case open
                    before<lb/> God, and he may give them.<lb/> But dear Charlie ought I to<lb/> be
                    recognized even as your<lb/>
                    <q>&ldquo;Ohio Sister,&rdquo;</q>; I fear if you knew<lb/> my reasons
                    you would but<lb/>
                    <pb n="3" entity="DSSR_000000766_0323"/> curse me, but it is<lb/> getting dark.</p>

            </div1>

            <div1 type="letter" n="2" id="d6">
                <head>Letter from Adelaide E. Case to Charles N. Tenney, Morning of <date
                        value="1861-12-20">December 20th, 1861</date></head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Friday Morn. Dec 20th<lb/></dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Charley,</salute></opener>

                <p> I thought I should<lb/> finish this, to me, painful letter<lb/> last night, but
                    found myself so<lb/> excited that I could not.<lb/> I will now try to do
                    it.<lb/>
                </p>

                <p>Dear Charlie, how your last letter<lb/> saddened the heart of Addie. In
                    speaking<lb/> of the possibility that you might<lb/> fall in the defense of your
                    country.<lb/></p>
                <p>Yes, dear Charlie you would be<lb/> deeply regretted by Addie. She<lb/> would be
                    deprived of <hi rend="underline">one true<lb/> friend</hi>. But I must
                    dispel<lb/> such thoughts. I regretted very<lb/> much your leaving
                    Charleston.<lb/> I fear that you will be in a<lb/> much more dangerous
                    position<lb/> at Romney than at Charleston.<lb/>
                    <pb n="4" entity="DSSR_000000766_0324"/> but to Him who watches the<lb/>
                    sparrows when they fall would<lb/> I commend thee my brother.<lb/></p>
                <p> My efforts to protect thee are vain<lb/> without His assistance.<lb/></p>
                <p> I will send this by Capt. Wood<lb/> when he goes to his company.<lb/></p>

                <p> Please send me your address as<lb/> soon as convenient.<lb/>
                </p>

                <closer>Laurie sends love.<lb/> Believe me yours in sisterly love,<lb/>
                    <signed>Addie</signed></closer>
            </div1>
        </body>

